# Null for Missing Data

## Core Principle
Always use `null` to represent missing, unavailable, or not-yet-loaded data. Never use arbitrary fallback values like `0`, `""`, or hardcoded defaults that mask the absence of data.

## Why `null`?

- **Explicit intent**: `null` means "not available", `0` means "zero" (a valid value)
- **Type safety**: TypeScript enforces null checks before use
- **Honest UI**: Can show "—" or loading state instead of misleading zeros
- **Easier debugging**: Immediately see what data is missing
- **Future-proof**: Easy to add data sources later without confusion

## Rules

### 1. Data Not Provided by Source

When a data source (REST API, WebSocket, etc.) doesn't provide a field:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Explicit that data isn't available
interface PositionData {
  volume: number | null;        // WebSocket provides, REST doesn't
  restingOrders: number | null; // REST provides, WebSocket doesn't
}

function fromWebSocket(msg: any): PositionData {
  return {
    volume: msg.volume,       // WebSocket has this
    restingOrders: null,      // WebSocket doesn't have this
  };
}

function fromRestApi(pos: KalshiPosition): PositionData {
  return {
    volume: null,                          // REST doesn't have this
    restingOrders: pos.resting_order_count, // REST has this
  };
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Misleading defaults
function fromWebSocket(msg: any): PositionData {
  return {
    volume: msg.volume,
    restingOrders: 0,  // BAD: 0 orders vs unavailable are different!
  };
}
```

### 2. Data Not Yet Loaded

When data is being fetched asynchronously:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - null until loaded
interface PositionData {
  marketName: string | null;  // null until fetched from market API
}

const [balance, setBalance] = useState<number | null>(null);
const [currentPrice, setCurrentPrice] = useState<number | null>(null);
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Fake data while loading
const [balance, setBalance] = useState<number>(0);  // BAD: 0 balance vs loading?
const [currentPrice, setCurrentPrice] = useState<number>(0);  // BAD: 0¢ is a real price!
```

### 3. Calculated Values That Depend on Missing Data

When a calculation can't be performed due to missing inputs:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - null when calculation impossible
const unrealizedPnl = currentPrice !== null && costBasis !== null
  ? (currentPrice * quantity) - costBasis
  : null;

const pnl = positions.reduce((sum, p) => {
  if (p.pnl === null) return sum;  // Skip positions with unknown P&L
  return sum + p.pnl;
}, 0);
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Fake zero when we don't know
const unrealizedPnl = currentPrice !== null
  ? (currentPrice * quantity) - costBasis
  : 0;  // BAD: Looks like break-even, but we don't know!
```

### 4. Optional/Nullable Props

Component props that may not always be provided:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Explicit about optional data
interface MarketCardProps {
  lastPrice: number | null;
  volume24h: number | null;
}

function MarketCard({ lastPrice, volume24h }: MarketCardProps) {
  return (
    <>
      <Text>{lastPrice !== null ? formatDollars(lastPrice) : '—'}</Text>
      <Text>{volume24h !== null ? volume24h : '—'}</Text>
    </>
  );
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Default to zero
interface MarketCardProps {
  lastPrice?: number;  // defaults to undefined
  volume24h?: number;
}

function MarketCard({ lastPrice = 0, volume24h = 0 }: MarketCardProps) {
  return (
    <>
      <Text>{formatDollars(lastPrice)}</Text>  {/* Shows $0.00 when unknown */}
      <Text>{volume24h}</Text>  {/* Shows 0 when unknown */}
    </>
  );
}
```

## Display Layer Patterns

### Numeric Values

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Show em dash for null
<Text>{volume !== null ? volume : '—'}</Text>
<Text>{pnl !== null ? formatDollarsWithSign(pnl) : '—'}</Text>
<Text>{lastPrice !== null ? formatDollars(lastPrice) : 'Loading...'}</Text>
```

### Conditional Rendering

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Only show if data exists
{restingOrders !== null && restingOrders > 0 && (
  <Badge>{restingOrders} open orders</Badge>
)}

{volume !== null && (
  <Text>Volume: {volume}</Text>
)}
```

### Aggregations

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Skip null values in calculations
const totalVolume = positions
  .filter(p => p.volume !== null)
  .reduce((sum, p) => sum + p.volume!, 0);

const avgPrice = prices.filter(p => p !== null).length > 0
  ? prices.filter(p => p !== null).reduce((sum, p) => sum + p!, 0) / prices.filter(p => p !== null).length
  : null;
```

## When to Use Fallbacks (Rare Cases)

Only use fallback values in the **display layer** when necessary for UX:

```typescript
// ✅ ACCEPTABLE - Fallback only for display
<Heading>{marketName ?? ticker}</Heading>  // Show ticker if name not loaded
<Text>{description ?? 'No description available'}</Text>

// But store as null internally:
interface Market {
  ticker: string;
  marketName: string | null;  // null until loaded
  description: string | null;
}
```

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

### ❌ Magic Numbers

```typescript
// BAD - 0 means both "zero" and "unknown"
volume: msg.volume || 0

// BAD - -1 as "unknown" flag
currentPrice: price ?? -1

// BAD - Empty string for missing text
marketName: name || ""
```

### ❌ Falsy Coercion

```typescript
// BAD - 0 is falsy, breaks null checks
if (volume) { ... }  // Skips both null AND 0!

// GOOD - Explicit null check
if (volume !== null) { ... }  // Only skips null
```

### ❌ Hidden Defaults in Calculation

```typescript
// BAD - Silently treats missing data as zero
const total = (a ?? 0) + (b ?? 0) + (c ?? 0);

// GOOD - Return null if any input is null
const total = a !== null && b !== null && c !== null
  ? a + b + c
  : null;
```

## TypeScript Configuration

Ensure strict null checks are enabled in `tsconfig.json`:

```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strictNullChecks": true,
    "strict": true
  }
}
```

## Summary

| Scenario | Use `null` | Don't Use |
|----------|-----------|-----------|
| Data not provided by source | ✅ `volume: null` | ❌ `volume: 0` |
| Data not yet loaded | ✅ `price: null` | ❌ `price: 0` |
| Calculation impossible | ✅ `pnl: null` | ❌ `pnl: 0` |
| Optional prop | ✅ `prop: T \| null` | ❌ `prop?: T` with default |
| Display fallback | ✅ `{val ?? '—'}` | ❌ Store as `0` |

**Golden Rule**: If you don't have the data, say so with `null`. Don't pretend you have it with a fake value.
